After a huge amount of hacking and printing of array values I managed to recreate the bad calculation in Python, which is due to a bug in the [Hann Window](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Window_function#Hann_window) on [Line 116 of audio_effect_spectrum_analyzer.cpp](https://github.com/godotengine/godot/blob/master/servers/audio/effects/audio_effect_spectrum_analyzer.cpp#L116) 

Basically there is a confusion due to a doubling of the size of the fft_size (beyond the doubling necessary to represent complex numbers and the doubling for the two stereo channels) resulting in the cosine wave being doubled.

Paste the following code into Jupyter Notebooks to plot these graphs.

```Python
%matplotlib inline
import math
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

freq = 44100; Hz = 440.0; N = 4096; phase = 0.85

def window_correct(x):
    return -0.5*math.cos(x*2*math.pi)+0.5
yval_correct = [ math.sin(2*math.pi*(i*Hz/freq+phase))*window_correct(i/(N-1))  for i in range(N) ]
