godotengine/godot-proposals#11797.body:
### Describe the project you are working on

A [tensor math computation library](https://github.com/Ivorforce/NumDot), which would like to be fast and easy to use (hence this proposal).

### Describe the problem or limitation you are having in your project

There are currently two 'grades' of objects in Godot:

- `Variant` types: These are identified with `Variant::Type` (`int32`), and use `Variant::_data` to store a custom payload that fits in 20 bytes. Some `Variant` types use the payload to manage a bigger payload somewhere on the heap.
- `Object` types: These are all the same `Variant` type, which is essentially a pointer to a heap payload.

`Variant` types are "hardcoded" in Godot, which means a fixed number of these exist. It is impossible to add new ones.
This is unfortunate because `Object` types come with a lot of overhead: They have a lot of boilerplate that may not be relevant to some subclasses, and automatically register in the `ObjectDB`. This makes them large and slow, and thus inappropriate for small types like `Vector2`. This makes some potential data types slower than they need to be, and others are effectively unusable.

### Describe the feature / enhancement and how it helps to overcome the problem or limitation

It would be possible to keep track of additional `Variant` types in a global registry. Whenever `Variant` types of unknown type are encountered, it is either appropriate to error out (as is already the case in most spots), or the respective `VariantDB` entry is asked to handle the case appropriately.

Here I list examples of uses for this system. See comments below the proposal for real-world use-cases:

#### Tiny data types

It would be possible for GDExtensions and modules to add more 'tiny' data types which fit in the available 20 bytes of payload. These would be analogous to existing types such as `Vector2`, with only an added overhead of a table lookup and a function call for operations.

I have shown [below](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/11797#issuecomment-2668159849) that tiny data types are about 17x faster as `Variant` than as `RefCounted` (construction and destruction).

#### Specialized Collection Types

A difficulty to add new `Variant` types is often cited as the reason new ones are not added.
For example, it would be possible to add new container types, such as `Set`, `Queue` and `Stack`. However, the overhead of `Object` would make these too slow for normal use, and `Array` exists and fills the need decently enough. Like this, Godot is barred from having more mature collection types. Through custom variant types, more could be added by GDExtensions (and possibly modules, if there's demand).

I have shown [below](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/11797#issuecomment-2668159849) that collection types are about 9x faster as `Variant` than as `RefCounted` (construction and destruction).

Personally, I would use custom `Variant` types for `Tensor` / `NDArray` objects in my GDExtension [NumDot](https://github.com/Ivorforce/NumDot). The performance benefit is well worth it here.

#### Improvement of modularity

Some existing data types are complex enough to warrant being moved to this system, alleviating the burden from `Variant` itself.
In particular, all existing collections types may be good candidates for this.

#### Relation to other proposals

I believe custom `Variant` types are versatile and could either facilitate other proposals, improve upon their potential gain, or even partially or fully supersede them. Most interestingly, some may be implementable as extensions that weren't before. List is WIP:

**[GDScript Structs](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/7329):** I believe this proposal is orthogonal, because the types are needed for different reasons. In fact, I believe the two proposals complement each other perfectly!
- `struct` related proposals are mainly concerned with providing a solution to `GDScript` users, with pre-defined storage strategies based on `Variant`. This proposal is mainly concerned with exposing the `Variant` payload to GDExtension / modules / the engine itself, to allow for the highest performance types possible. The custom `Variant` provider can choose any storage strategy, including memory pools, pass-by-reference, or copy-on-write.
- GDScript Structs could be implemented using custom `Variant` types, which may alleviate the burden to do this from Godot core to `GDScript`. Whether or not that's desirable is worth discussing.
- The implementation proposed here may be able to make use of existing systems, e.g. for custom operators or adding methods, while this may have to be implemented from scratch for new `struct` types.

**[GDScript Structs (Variant edition)](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/2816)**: This earlier proposal suggested storing GDScript structs in the payload of the `Variant`, much like how the payload is made accessible in this proposal. The main difference is that #2816 was concerned with proposing GDScript accessible structs, while this proposal is concerned with making payloads available to GDExtensions, modules, and the engine, to add new high-efficiency types. This reflects on the differences in proposed APIs. There are other differences in implementation details as well, which are worth discussing.

**[Custom Operator Overloads](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/8383):** Overloading operators such as `+` is most useful on types that are fast. `Variant` types are the fastest, and they _already_ support custom operator overloads through existing APIs. Implementing overloads for `Object` types (e.g. GDScript classes) could still be useful, but most use-cases would be better served with custom `Variant` types for efficiency concerns.

**[Set (Collection)](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/867):** Sets may still be useful in native Godot, but with custom `Variant` types, they could be implemented via `GDExtension` at no loss of speed.

**[PackedFloat16Array and PackedInt16Array](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/11348):** These types could be added through GDExtension instead of adding them to core, although they also wouldn't interact with core then.

**[PackedVector2iArray and PackedVector3iArray](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/5486):** These types could be added through GDExtension instead of adding them to core, although they also wouldn't interact with core then.

**[unsigned int type](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/9740):** It would be possible to add unsigned int types via GDExtension, although it probably wouldn't be sufficient for many use-cases if not accepted into Core itself because it wouldn't interface great with Godot functions. For some use-cases though, GDExtension unsigned ints might be "good enough".

**[Reduced Precision int / float types](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/866):** It would be possible to add custom `float16` etc. (although I'm not sure I see the point in this).

**[GDScript Generics](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/1207):** The most common use-case for generics is generic containers. Due to performance implications (such as `Object` and GDScript overhead), the most appropriate format for containers is `Variant` types. While generic classes for `GDScript` would undoubtedly enjoy great popularity, support for custom `Variant` types is a better fit for collections (and possibly other generic types).

**Domain-specific math types**, such as:
- [Oriented Bounding Box (OBB)](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/12790)
- [Pose](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/13510)
- [Hex map coordinate](https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/11797#issuecomment-2867695784)

These make great candidates for a custom `Variant` type. Most of these domain specific types would probably be provided / used by GDExtensions, but on high demand, they could be added to Godot Core too.

### Describe how your proposal will work, with code, pseudo-code, mock-ups, and/or diagrams

**Note:** Implementing this feature would ideally build upon https://github.com/godotengine/godot-proposals/issues/12321, which would already add half the work required. 

**I have an [experimental active branch](https://github.com/godotengine/godot/compare/master...Ivorforce:godot:custom-variant-types) with the feature working, along with a short [demo](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/18865273/new-game-project-custom-variants.zip).**

`Variant::Type` is already `int32`, which has more than enough slots to harbour custom data types. Extensions and modules could register new data types in a registry, which generates a `Variant::Type` ID for the new type. The inserted entry is queried when operations are performed on the `Variant` in question.

The registry could be managed by modules and GDExtensions like:

```c++
class MyVariantType : CustomVariantType {
    static int type_id = 0;

    override void reference(Variant &p_variant, Variant &p_arg) {
        // Do custom things, e.g.
        p_variant.data = p_arg.data;
    }
}

MyVariantType::type_id = VariantDB::add_type(info);
```

The IDs that are handed out are `transient` across runs. They are not guaranteed to be the same on the next run.
To account for this, serialized `Variant` types would identify itself through a `StringName` or `UUID` (not sure which is better suited). High volume data types storing large volumes of `Variant` would need to establish their own registries in the data type to improve efficiency - although I don't _think_ Godot actually uses any of these.

Here's an example of how the `VariantDB` could be used in `Variant::reference`:

```c++
void Variant::reference(const Variant &p_variant) {
// [...]
	switch (p_variant.type) {
// [...]

		case PACKED_VECTOR4_ARRAY: {
			_data.packed_array = static_cast<PackedArrayRef<Vector4> *>(p_variant._data.packed_array)->reference();
			if (!_data.packed_array) {
				_data.packed_array = PackedArrayRef<Vector4>::create();
			}
		} break;
		default: {
			// Registry managed data type
			VariantDB::get(p_variant.type).reference(*this, p_variant);
		}
	}
}
```

There should be no observable cost to existing `Variant` types.

### If this enhancement will not be used often, can it be worked around with a few lines of script?

No.

### Is there a reason why this should be core and not an add-on in the asset library?

It's core.

