### Describe the project you are working on

Patchwork, a real-time version control plugin for Godot.

### Describe the problem or limitation you are having in your project

Currently, there's no way to retrieve a list of unsaved scenes. If a plugin wants to write files on-disk, there's no way to know if scenes are "safe" to update.

### Describe the feature / enhancement and how it helps to overcome the problem or limitation

Create a method `EditorInterface::get_unsaved_scenes()`, and expose it to the public API. This allows plugin authors to know both that there **are** unsaved scenes, as well as **which** scenes are unsaved and therefore unsafe to update.

### Describe how your proposal will work, with code, pseudo-code, mock-ups, and/or diagrams

PR here: https://github.com/godotengine/godot/pull/113767

The method:

- Iterates through `EditorNode::get_editor_data().get_edited_scenes()`
- Checks undo-redo history to determine if the scene is saved
- Returns a list of scene paths

Here is the method in question:
```c++
PackedStringArray EditorInterface::get_unsaved_scenes() const {
	PackedStringArray ret;
	Vector<EditorData::EditedScene> scenes = EditorNode::get_editor_data().get_edited_scenes();

	for (EditorData::EditedScene &edited_scene : scenes) {
		if (edited_scene.root == nullptr) {
			continue;
		}
		String scene_path = edited_scene.root->get_scene_file_path();
		if (EditorUndoRedoManager::get_singleton()->is_history_unsaved(edited_scene.history_id)) {
			ret.push_back(scene_path);
			continue;
		}
		// Check if scene has unsaved changes in built-in resources.
		for (int j = 0; j < EditorNode::get_editor_data().get_editor_plugin_count(); j++) {
			if (!EditorNode::get_editor_data().get_editor_plugin(j)->get_unsaved_status(scene_path).is_empty()) {
				ret.push_back(scene_path);
				continue;
			}
		}
	}
	return ret;
}
```

### If this enhancement will not be used often, can it be worked around with a few lines of script?

As far as I know, there is no current workaround.

### Is there a reason why this should be core and not an add-on in the asset library?

Yes, this method uses internal methods to retrieve a list of unsaved scenes.

godotengine/godot-proposals#13815.body:
### Describe the project you are working on

Patchwork, a real-time version control plugin for Godot.

### Describe the problem or limitation you are having in your project

When checking out a new branch in our version control plugin, sometimes a file will be removed from the working directory. When a user has a text file open in the Script Editor, that file might then be outdated, and need closing. 

### Describe the feature / enhancement and how it helps to overcome the problem or limitation

Add `ScriptEditor::close_file(path)`, which closes a script at a given path. 

This is similar to `EditorInterface::close_scene()`, but for script files.

### Describe how your proposal will work, with code, pseudo-code, mock-ups, and/or diagrams

PR here: https://github.com/godotengine/godot/pull/113772

Here's the method:
```c++
void ScriptEditor::close_file(const String &p_file) {
	for (int i = 0; i < tab_container->get_tab_count(); i++) {
		ScriptEditorBase *se = Object::cast_to<ScriptEditorBase>(tab_container->get_tab_control(i));
		if (!se) {
			continue;
		}
		if (se->get_edited_resource()->get_path() == p_file) {
			_close_tab(i, false, false);
			break;
		}
	}
}
```

### If this enhancement will not be used often, can it be worked around with a few lines of script?

I don't know of a (good, stable) workaround that doesn't involve hacking the UI.

### Is there a reason why this should be core and not an add-on in the asset library?

Yes, this adds functionality to the ScriptEditor which relies on internal methods.
